------------<br>
<br>
This was deliberate and pointed out as such in the patch message. Before that patch (maybe a couple of months after release iirc ?), damage adds didn't stack AT ALL. So Mythic decided to introduce the stacking code, however, fearing to get skyrocketing dmg add values, they decided to cut down the &quot;smallest&quot; damage add by half, to balance things a bit and mitigate the total damage add.<br>
However the developer who made this decision looked only at Albion situation (at that time, it was a pretty heated topic : Mythic visibly had less time to design Midgard and Hibernia, and Albion was the only really &quot;finished&quot; realm - the situation is much better now <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  ), where, basically, elementalists have a very strong castable dmg add (10dps at level 50, baseline), and paladins a moderate &quot;chant&quot; dmg add (similar to skald's).<br>
So the rule was set to the following : total dmg add = castable damage add + half the &quot;chant&quot; damage add<br>
<br>
The forumla worked quite well for Albion ... but not in Migard, and to a lesser extent in Hibernia ... . It works ok in the thane+skald situation. However, skalds have a similar, or even better damage add than a typical shaman or runemaster (unless heavily specced in darkness). So, the stacking code only give marginal bonuses typically (you'd better be singing speed or a resist song), and can even in some cases be detrimental, with a low spec shaman damage add.<br>
<br>
So the rule should be changed to this one : total damage add = strongest damage add + half the weakest damage add.<br>
<br>
Or even get rid of the 50% reduction at all. 6 monthes ago, it was a legitimate concern to avoid giving too much power to damage add, they feared game balance repercussion, but I think we can say with confidence that it won't matter that much ... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#d1c2a2><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub36.ezboard.com/bteamskald.showUserPublicProfile?gid=maximumstorage>MaximumStorage</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Team Skald Contributor</span><br>  Posts: 43<br> <font color=#ff0000>(11/16/02 12:20 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub36.ezboard.com/fteamskaldfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=384.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> resist chant combining</span><hr size=1> IMO I think combining resist chants is not something for skalds. They wouldnt give us a non-power draining version and we all  know that skalds use power up too fast to even consider using power-over-time on a resist chant.  In  order to run resist chant ya need 2 skalds anyway because 1 skald is running dmg add, if you're not running dmg add in close melee, you are not being effective. It's simply the best chant we have and there is very little reason to  use anything else unless you have 2-3 skalds per group. Let's work on changing that by making a new type of chant worth using besides dmg add. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#efe0c0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub36.ezboard.com/bteamskald.showUserPublicProfile?gid=pranzer>Pranzer</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Team Skald Contributor</span><br>  Posts: 33<br> <font color=#ff0000>(11/18/02 12:52 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub36.ezboard.com/fteamskaldfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=384.topic&index=23>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: resist chant combining</span><hr size=1> I